column168: A shipment of hazardous waste was on the dock at the intermediate truck transfer facility.  While being loaded onto a trailer destined for the intended waste disposal facility, a drum fell off of the pallet onto the floor.  When it struck the floor, the lid was dislodged, causing a spill.  The drum was immediately uprighted.  A response crew was summoned, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and cleaned up the spilled material from the dock.  The lid was put back on the trailer and the absorbent material used to clean up the spill was put into a container for incineration at the facility.  The shipment was loaded onto the trailer without further incident.

column168: On February 10, 2015 at 1230 ET, The driver of a CTL Transportation tractor (C16480) MC307 tanker (C21988) noticed a small drip on the asphalt below while performing a routine check. A cleanup contractor was immediately dispatched and responded to the scene. Approximately 1 ounce of material released from the pressure relief valve (PRV) due to a loose threading inside of the pressure relief device. The release had already evaporated before the contractor arrived on site. The device was cleaned, re-taped and re-threaded then a slosh test was performed. The device checked clear and the CTMV continued to its destination.
A pin size hole was found on the bag.  The bag was able to be repaired and shipped back to the customer.
The drum was over filled and a small amount is spilled on top of the drum.  ERTS was contacted to clean the spill.

On February 10, 2015 at 1210 ET, the driver of an R&L tractor trailer (26551L) was lowering the lift-gate during the unloading phase at the consignee's location when a 275-gallon tote slid off and dropped upside down to the concrete area below. No soils, drains or waterways were reported to have been impacted by the release. A cleanup contractor was immediately dispatched and responded. Approximately 2 gallons released from the cap and top of the tote. The tote was transferred into a new 275-gallon tote. The release was neutralized then was cleaned up with granular absorbents. All generated waste was taken by the contractor for pending disposal.

column168: DURING THE RAIL-TO-TRUCK TRANSLOADING OF FERRIC CHLORIDE SOLUTION THERE WAS A COMMUNICATION FAILURE BETWEEN THE BULK LOADER AND THE TRUCK DRIVER. THE DRIVER WAS MONITORING THE LEVEL OF THE PRODUCT INSIDE THE TANK TRAILER AND WAS POSITIONED NEAR THE MANWAY OF THE TRAILER. THE LOADER HAD PARTIALLY CLOSED THE UNLOADING VALVE TO ALLOW THE DRIVER TO CHECK THE LIQUID LEVEL. AT SOME POINT THE DRIVER REMOVED HIS HARD HAT AND FACE SHIELD TO IMPROVE HIS SIGHT OF THE PRODUCT. THE LOADER OPENED THE LIQUID VALVE TO THE FULL OPEN POSITION WHICH CAUSED A SURGE IN PRODUCT AND ALSO CAUSED THE PRODUCT TO SPLASH OUT OF THE TRAILER. BECAUSE HE WAS NOT WEARING PPE, PRODUCT ENTERED THE EYES OF THE DRIVER. HIS EYES WERE RINSED OUT FOR 15 MINUTES AT THE LOCATION BUT EMS WAS NOTIFIED AND TOOK HIM TO THE HOSPITAL FOR FURTHER EVALUATION AND TREATMENT. HE SUBSEQUENTLY RETURNED TO THE JOBSITE. ALL SPILLED MATERIAL WAS TAKEN UP WITH ABSORBENT MATERIALS. IT IS ESTIMATED THAT NO MORE THAN TEN GALLONS WERE RELEASED.
column169: AFFECTED EMPLOYEES HAVE BEEN RE-TRAINED WITH REGARD TO THE PPE POLICY FOR ALL EMPLOYEES AND NON-EMPLOYEES. EMPLOYEES HAVE ALSO BEEN ADVISED THAT DRIVERS NOT WEARING THE PROPER PPE MUST NOT BE LOADED. THIS WOULD NOT HAVE PREVENTED THE SPILL BUT MAY HAVE PREVENTED THE INJURY. ENHANCED COMMUNICATION BETWEEN DRIVER AND LOADER WAS ALSO REVIEWED.

column42: RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL, TYPE A PACKAGE NON-SPECIAL FORM, NON FISSILE OR FISSILE-EXCEPTED
column168: Driver arrived at consignee. Portal monitors detected the presence of radiation on the trailer. Based on the reports of the statement of the driver, the trailer did not alert the portal monitors upon exiting the facility after delivery of the shipment. Item was a photographic lens which had been in DoD storage. Shipped to consignee in crate.   Based on the level of radioactivity provided by DoD in an email received on 2/5/2015: BLUF: Dose levels are not at a level that would cause a health or safety concern. Survey results from MCAAP RSO indicated a package surface dose rate of 3.9 mR/hr using a Ludlum Model 2241-2 Ratemeter/Scaler coupled to a Geiger-Mueller Probe. The instrument was current with its calibration. 3.9 mR/hr was stated by DoD as a possible overestimation as a GM will tend to over respond due to the lower energy gammas and beta that would not be in the Cesium-137 used for calibration.     No Tl, basic description or other required information provided on the shipping paper or package to assist in identifying this shipment as a hazardous material shipment. Yellow II label believed to have been needed based on surface activity level. Classification of material based on information stated in this report.
column169: DoD should review their process for handling these types of materials.

column168: A Clean Harbor's driver was loading his vacuum tanker when he noticed that a small amount of material was leaking from the level gauge of his vacuum tanker. The driver immediatly put down sorbent pads and a bucket to contain the leaking material.The driver then contacted his home dispatcher to inform them of the leak. column168: Shipper was loading a Phenol railcar on 02/17/15 at around 23:59pm. The meter was set for 21,200 gallons minus 115 gal for the heel, so it was set for 21,050 gallons to load. Once loading began the shipper realized he used the incorrect heel volume and stopped the meter to enter new load amount. Shipper reset the meter and subtracted the additional 3000 lbs from the meter and reset the meter for the heel. (original heel was 1000, new heel was 4000).(460-115) for 345 GAL.  This amount was subtracted from 11,493 for a reset amount of 11,148 gallons.  So 22,641 gallons could have went into the car total, but it was stopped short. Tank level went from 15.24 – 12.11 before the loading was stopped, so 3.13 ft delta at 306 GPI.  So we loaded 11493 into the car. The total car capacity is 22018 gallons, minus the 460 gallon heel. The tank car could hold then 21,558 gallons.      22,546 gallons went out of VT-339 phenol loading tankand into a tank car with a capacity of 21,558, for an overflow amount of 988 gallons. This spill was a result of an overfill due to a calculation error made by the loader, this was not a result of any issues with the railcar or loading process.
column169: A robust investigation was performed on this incident to identify root cause of the incident and what "Mistake proof" measures that can be implemented to prevent this type of spill in the future. The investigation identified 7 actions that are being taken to prevent going forward.  1. Engineering project implemented to install overflow protection that would prevent a spill if human error is made in loading calcuations.  2. Improved operating procedures- Railserve will be required to ensure all cars are uncoupled during the weighing process for accurate heel volume.   3. Update procedure for loaders - Shippers will be required to review scale tickets and record the heel vs calling on the phone to get heel verbally. Eliminates miscommunication of heel volume.  4. Update procedure on how to operate meter if it needs to be stopped in the middle of a load, explain details for each meter.  5. Update procedure if meter volume is accidentally cleared or power failure after loading has started. Car will be required to be re-weighed to determine how much volume is left in the car and how to reset meter to finish load without overfill.  6. Procedure updated on how to recalculate load volume for each meter style.  7. Update all railcar loading procedures on the above actions and train all loaders on the improved procedures.

ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT (EMI) JOB #35986: ON 02-03-15, AT APPROXIMATELY 0930 HOURS (ETZ)AN SA WHITE OIL COMPANY, INC. (SAWOC) DRIVER WAS MAKING A DELIVERY OF FUELS (GASOLINE AND DIESEL FUEL) TO THE HERTZ RENTAL EQUIPMENT (HERTZ) FACILITY. DRIVER HAD SUCCESSFULLY TRANSFERRED 404 GALLONS OF GASOLINE FROM CARGO TRUCK TO THE GASOLINE STORAGE TANK. DRIVER THEN CONNECTED TRANSFER HOSE FROM CARGO TRUCK DIESEL FUEL COMPARTMENT TO THE ABOVE-GROUND DIESEL STORAGE TANK AND BEGAN TRANSFERRING THE DIESEL FUEL. THE DRIVER THEN PROCEEDED TO RE-ENTER THE CAB OF THE ARGO TRUCK TO COMPLETE SOME PAPERWORK WHILE DIESEL FUEL WAS BEING TRANSFERRED. DUE TO THE SURROUNDING NOISE, THE DRIVER WAS NOT AWARE THAT THE STORAGE TANK WAS OVERFILLED UNTIL HE WAS ALERTED BY A HERTZ EMPLOYEE. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY STOPPED THE TRANSFER PROCESS AND CONTACTED HIS OFFICE TO NOTIFY THEM OF THE RELEASE.    AT 0947 HOURS (CTZ) MR. TIRSO BELTRAN OF EMI RECEIVED A CALL FROM MR. ROBERT THORNTON (SAWOC) REQUESTING ASSISTANCE IN REGARDS TO THE RELEASE. 407 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL HAD BEEN RELEASED. THE RELEASE HAD IMPACTED THE AREA CONCRETE AREA WHERE THE STORAGE TANK WAS LOCATED. AN UNKNOWN AMOUNT HAD IMPACTED A STORM DRAIN.  MR. THORNTON STATED THAT SAWOC WOULD MANAGE THE CLEANUP OF THE IMPACTED AREA OF THE CONCRETE BUT REQUESTED THAT EMI MANAGER THE REMEDIATION OF THE IMPACTED STORM DRAIN.  MR. THORNTON STATED THAT HERTZ HAD MADE NOTIFICATIONS TO THE LOCAL AND STATE AUTHORITIES.    MR. BELTRAN CONTACTED SWS ENVIRONMENTAL SEVICES (SWS) AND EMI ENVIRONMENTAL SUBCONTRACTOR AND REQUESTED THAT THEY RESPOND.    SWS ARRIVED ON SITE.  THE OUTFALL OF THE STORM DRAIN SYSTEM WAS LOCATED AND IT WAS OBSERVED THAT IT DISCHARGED INTO AN NAMELESS TRIBUTARY (CREEK) APPROXIMATELY 1/4 MILE FROM THE RELEASE SITE. SWS UTILIZED ABSORBENT BOOM, ABSORBENT PAD, AND CONSTRUCTED AN UNDERFLOW DAM TO CONTAIN THE DIESEL FUEL. ABSORBENT PAD UTILIZED TO RECOVER AS MUCH DIESEL FUEL AS POSSIBLE. A VACUUM TRUCK WAS ALSO UTILIZED TO RECOVER THE FUEL. THE STORM DRAIN SYSTEM WAS FLUSHED WITH COPIUS AMOUNTS OF WATER TO REMOVE THE DIESEL FUEL FROM THE STORM DRAIN SYSTEM. THE VACUUM TRUCK RECOVERED THE DIESEL FUEL AT THE UNDERFLOW DAM. APPROXIMATELY 275 TO 290 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL-WATER MIXTURE WAS RECOVERED. ABSORBENT BOOM WAS LEFT IN PLACE IN AREAS OF THE CREEK AND WOULD BE MONITORED PENDING THE NEXT RAIN EVENT. ONCE IT IS OBSERVED THAT THERE IS NO IMPACT TO THE ABSORBENT BOOM, THE ABSORBENT BOOM WILL BE REMOVED.    ALL IMPACTED ABSORBENT MATERIALS WERE PLACED IN A ROLL-OFF BOX.  THE WASTE WILL BE PROFILED FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.  UPON COMPLETION OF THE PROJECT AND RECEIVING WASTE DISPOSAL APPROVAL, THE WASTE WILL BE TRANSPORTED TO THE APPROVED DISPOSAL FACILITY FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.
column169: CONTINUE OUR ONGOING EFFORTS IN DRIVER SAFETY/SPILL PREVENTION IN EFFORTS IN PREVENTING INCIDENTS AS THESE FROM HAPPENING.  INSURE DRIVERS ARE PROPERLY TRAINED FOR SITE-SPECIFIC LOADING/UNLOADING PROCEDURES.

column168: There was no package failure. Driver was unloading into the customer's tank, and customer was on top of tank and stated that there was still 2 feet of room in top of tank. Customer climbed down and tank ran over. Driver stated about 10 gallons spilled onto the ground. Customer told driver that it was OK and they would clean it up and signed the driver bills and told him he could leave. After driver left, customer then stated that about 700 to 900 gallons spilled onto ground. There is no way because it would have taken 10 to 15 minutes for the driver to spill this much. I reported to NRC to be on the safe side. We have not heard back from the customer or anyone at the plant in reference to any cleanup or loss of product. Nor has our Insurance Carrier heard from anyone. We have learned that the customer has an uncapped loading hose that hangs out of the tank with no cutoff valve, and this possibly could be where they spilt the product after our driver left the plant.
column169: Horizon Tank Lines trains all of our drivers in the handling of Hazardous Materials and require immediate notification of any spills. Our driver followed his training and swears that he only spilt about 10 gallons which would have been almost the RQ of 100 gallons.

column168: On February 1, 2015, a Dupre Logistics DOT 406 tanker experienced a fuel overfill of UN1993 Diesel fuel. The overfill caused the release of approximately 265 gallons to the asphalt lot, nearby soil, as well as a nearby storm drain.  Most of the fuel went into the drain, which was found to lead south approximately 200 ft. to the next drain and subsequently into a sump drain where most of the fuel appeared to be pooled. Contractors worked with the fire department to flush the drain and remove any potential residual fuel contained within. All contaminated solid and liquid materials were containerized for disposal.

column168: Intermodal trailer FW 12688 was reported leaking a clear liquid substance after its arrival at the BNSF intermodal facility. FW 12688 was carefully moved to the facility's containment area. Contract responder's inspection of FW 12688 revealed one palletized 55 gallon steel drum (UN Specification 1A1/Y1.8/300/15/USA/NCCC) with a hazardous material label indicating a flammable liquid material was leaking from its bottom rolling hoop. It appeared that this drum had rubbed against an adjacent drum on the pallet resulting in a small hole/crack along the rolling hoop. These drums (three per pallet) were banded together on the pallet with shrink wrap that allowed drum movement during transit. The lading within FW 12688 had shifted towards the rear doorway indicating that blocking and bracing of the lading within FW 12688 was insufficient. The responders patched the hole in the leaking drum and placed it into an over-pack drum properly labeled. Spillage within FW 12688 was cleaned and all removed lading was returned inside FW 12688, blocked and braced for further over the road transportation. Appropriate placards were applied onto the exterior of FW 12688.   The SDS for this leaking commodity from the manufacturer (Bradley Coatings Group) indicated that this commodity is a hazardous material (UN 1263, Paint, Class 3, PG II) in transportation and this information was not passed to the BNSF at the time of initial rail transit by the shipper carrier (First West Express).     The responders also noted 'Corrosive Placards' laying atop drums inside FW 12688. They also observed drums and totes/IBCs of corrosive materials /disinfectant solutions inside FW 12688. In particular, 55 gallon steel drums of UN 1903, Disinfectants, Liquid, Corrosive NOS (Quaternary Ammonium Compound), Class 8, PG II were observed. A total inventory of these undeclared corrosive materials was not provided.
column169: Ensure shipper cariier provides accurate hazardous material shipping information and documentation for hazardous material intermodal shipments. The carrier (First West Express Inc.) was counseled by a BNSF LARS (Load and Ride Solutions) representative on required identification and appropriate hazardous material descriptions on bills of lading presented for rail transportation.

column168: During a BNSF mechanical inspection of an outbound train in the railyard, the inspector reported commodity odor emanating from entrained tank car FURX 120077. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder immediately inspected FURX 120077. The responder reported no liquid release observed. Manway closure inspection revealed all six manway securement eyebolts were tool tight, but an audible vapor hiss was emanating from the manway closure. Inspection of the manway gasket condition revealed the applied nozzle gasket was partially torn/shredded, thus not providing a good seal. The deteriorated manway gasket was replaced by a new manway nozzle gasket. The manway closure was then properly secured. Afterwards, no further commodity odor or vapor hiss was detectable. Intact shipper seal TBS 271984 at the manway closure was replaced by seal BNSF 06157819. Response was concluded by 1345 hrs. PST, 2/03/2015.  The qualification stencil on FURX 120077 indicated that its last tank qualification was in the year 2006.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: THE DRIVER COMPLETED THE TRANSFER OF A CHROMIUM-IMPACTED WASTEWATER FROM THE CUSTOMER'S ON-SITE STORAGE TANKS TO THE ENVRITE OF PENNSYLVANIA TANKER TRUCK. UPON COMPLETETION OF PAPERWORK, THE TRUCK WAS CLEARED TO LEAVE THE SITE. IMMEDIATELY AFTER LEAVING THE CUSTOMER SITE, THE DRIVER NOTICED LIQUID LEAKING FROM THE REAR OF THE TANKER. AS SOON AS SAFELY POSSIBLE, THE DRIVER PULLED OFF OF THE THOROGHFARE TO DETERMINE THE CAUSE OF THE LEAK. UPON INPSECTION, HE NOTICED THAT THE REAR HATCH DOME LID HAD BEEN CLOSED BUT NOT FULLY SECURED PRIOR TO LEAVING THE CUSTOMER SITE.  HE IMMEDIATELY TIGHTENED THE REAR HATCH AND THE LEAK STOPPED.    THE DRIVER WAS INSTRUCTED TO RETURN TO THE CUSTOMER SITE, NOTIFY THE CUSTOMER OF THE RELEASE AND ASSIST WITH ANY NECESSARY CLEANUP. UPON RETURN, THE CUSTOMER HAD ALREADY NOTICED THE DISCOLORED WATER THAT SPILLED ON THE CONTAINMENT PAD AND ONTO THE ASPHALT LEADING FROM THE CONTAINMENT PAD. CLEAN UP ACTIVITIES HAD ALREADY BEGUN.  THE DRIVER STAYED ON-SITE AND ASSISTED WITH CLEANUP UNTIL IT WAS DETERMINED TO BE COMPLETE AT 4:30 PM.    PLEASE SEE THE ATTACHED HONEYWELL SPILL INCIDENT REPORT LETTERS AND MDE REPORT.

At approximately 0108 hours a Nadone Cyclohexanone tank car was started loading at Spot 17 of the Honeywell, Resins and Chemicals, Area 6, Tank Farm.  At approximately 0315 hours a field operator discovered the car overflowing.  The field operator immediately stopped the loading operation and notified supervision.  Operations transferred Nadone Cyclohexanone from the containment sump to a holding tank and applied speedy dry to a gravel area that Nadone Cyclohexanone entered.  Operations washed down the area.  Nadone Cyclohexanone loading at Spot 17 was suspended until containment actions were in place.  The overflow resulted in an approximate 15 gallon Nadone spill into a gravel area near a containment sump.      The investigation found that the automatic transfer valve did not close as designed when the level reached its trip point and the load limit of the loading meter was met due to a frozen actuator.  The actuator was unfrozen and wrapped with temporary insulation.
column169: The actuator valve was rewrapped with permanent insulation to protect from cold weather.

A vehicle operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc was en route from the shipper’s location to the intended waste management facility.  During the course of the trip, the driver made a routine stop at a 10 day transfer facility for the purpose of consolidating less than truck load quantities on a single transport vehicle for continued transportation. During the transfer operation, it was discovered that approximately 10 ounces of material had  escaped from the valve on the container. Facility personnel assembled a response team and proceeded to place the compromised container into a secondary containment pallet and prepared for repackagin into sutable containers.  In addition, all clean-up debris and materials used to decontaminate the floor of the trailer were collected and placed into the salvage drum. Once complete, the container was secured and was placed onto the trailer for continued transportation.

column168: Trailer 51, which is a fiberglass trailer, was loaded on February 6th.  The driver picked up the trailer on Saturday, February 7th at approximately 16:00 and then drove six hours north to Madawaska, ME.  The driver spent the night at the plant in preparation for his scheduled delivery on Sunday, February 8th at 09:00.  The temperature overnight was -20 degrees (factoring in wind chill) and there was no freeze protection available for the trailer.      When the truck and trailer were positioned into the unloading area, the driver was going to air unload the product, however when the internal and external valves were opened, the driver found the internal valve was frozen and no product was being off-loaded.   The driver disconnected the line and closed both the internal valve, external valve and moved the unit so that it could be steamed.      The driver opened the external valve and placed the steam line in the product line, in between the internal and external valve.  Steaming had to be accomplished this way as the product line is made of fiberglass.  If the steam line were placed on the outside of the product line it would have burned and damaged.    While the steaming was taking place the driver waited in a rail shed because of the extremely cold weather conditions.  Approximately 15 minutes later, the security guard notified the driver that product was spilling from the trailer.  The driver shut the internal valve.  The nearby drain was blocked with snow and prevented any further product to be in released into the plant’s waste treatment system.      It was determined that the spill occurred due to the driver failing to visually verify the internal valve was closed by inspecting the knob on the air-actuated valve.  The driver believed he had closed the internal valve before he moved the trailer to be steamed, but later it was discovered that when he opened the valve it allowed some frozen product to wedge itself underneath the open internal valve, not allowing it to close.
column169: The driver did not follow company policy and FMCSR that he should always be in attendance monitoring trailer.  The driver was distracted by the extreme weather conditions.  He waited for the trailer to be steamed in the rail shed near the steam area, he did not maintain vision with the trailer.      The corrective action to prevent this type of release from reoccurring will entail the following:   • The details of the spill, root cause and corrective action will be sent out via Qualcomm message to the entire fleet of SBL. This is to remind all drivers of the hazards of leaving a vehicle unattended, a review of the company policy and the FMCSR.  It will show the importance of following their procedures of verifying securement especially when an unforeseen event or distraction takes place.    • The driver involved will complete the Pro-Tread lesson “Driver Distractions”   • The driver will complete re-training of company policy 13.4 unloading procedures.

column168: ISO TANK ILIU140005-0 WAS DROPPED FOR LOADING AT AFTON CHEMICAL ON FRIDAY 02/06/2015 WITH HITEC 369. DURING TRANSPORT TO THE UPRR ON 02/09/2015 SMALL AMOUNTS OF PRODUCT LEAKED FROM THE FLANGE GASKETS. ABOUT 1 PINT OF PRODUCT LEAKED INTO THE SPILL BOX AND DRAIN LUBES CAUSING A SMALL AMOUNT OF HITEC 369 TO BE SPILLED ON THE CONCRETE ROADWAY AT THE UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD.   UPON THE UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD (UPRR) NOTICING THE LEAK THEY HAD THE DRIVER REPOSITION THE LOAD TO A LESS TRAVELEED AREA. THE UNION PACIFIC CONTACTED IEMA (IL EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT AGENCY) FOR THE HAZARDOUS SPILL. MIDWEST SYSTEMS DISPATCHED A MECHANIC TO THE UPRR FOR REPAIRS. UPON ARRIVAL THE MECHANIC FOUND THREE (3) NUTS ON THE BOTTOM SIPHON TUBE THAT WERE ONLY HAND TIGHT AND NOT SET TO THE PROPER TORQUE SETTINGS. HE ALSO DISCOVERED THAT ONE (1) NUT ON THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE WAS LOOSE AS WELL. TO IMMEDIATELY FIX THE ISSUE THE MECHANIC TORQUED DOWN ALL NUTS ON THE TANK. THE PRODUCT WAS CLEANED FROM THE TANK, SPILL BOX AND CHASSIS USING RAGS AND CITRUS CLEANER. THE SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT THE LEADED ONTO THE GROUND WAS ABSORBED USING PIG MAT. ANY REMAINING RESIDUE WAS CLEANED UP USING DRY SWEEP, RAGS AND CITRUS CLEANER. ALL WAS WAS REMOVED IN A 5 GALLON BUCKET BY IEMA FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.   ROOT CAUSE: PRIOR TO LOADING, ILIU140005-0 WAS PRESSURE TESTED TO ENSURE NO LEAKS WERE DETECTED. DURING THE TEST THE MECHANIC FAILED TO FOLLOW THE SOP AND SOAP TEST ALL OF THE FITTINGS ON TOP OF THE TANK.  DURING OUT GATE INSPECTION THE NUTS APPEARED TO BE TIGHT-HOWEVER, WITHOUT THE PROPER TORQUE SETTINGS PRODUCT LEAKED FROM THE FLANGE GASKETS.
column169: In an effort to prevent future incidents all tank mechanics at Midwest Systems are required to review the SOP for pressure testing ISO tanks. During the test all valves and fittings will be soap tested at 1 BAR. This will include the bottom outlet valve, man lid, pressure relief valve, air inlet, blind flanges, and top discharged valve (if equipped). Failure to company with SOP will result in disciplinary measure ranging from suspension to termination. Midwest Systems has also created a new pressure test sheet. It includes a checklist for each mechanic to sign, during the test.

column169: THE ONE IMPORTANT THING IS TO REVIEW WITH THE UNLOADER THE PROPER WAY TO HANDLE HAZ MATS. MAKE SURE THEY UNDERSTAND THAT ARROWS ON THE BOX ARE THERE FOR A REASON AND THAT SHOULD ALWAYS BE FOLLOWED ALSO HAVE A PCM ABOUT THE INCIDENT SO THAT THIS KIND ACCIDENT DOES NOT HAPPEN AGAIN.

column168: THE SMITH SYSTEMS DRIVER PERFORMED A PRE-TRIP INSPECTION OF HIS TRACTOR/TRAILER UNIT AND NOTICED A LIQUID WITH A GASOLINE ODOR DRIPPING OUT OF HIS TRAILER. THE DRIVER NOTIFIED SMITH SYSTEMS CORPORATE WHO CONTACTED ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT INC WHO INITIATED THE RESPONSE. A LOCAL CLEANUP CREW ARRIVED ONSITE AND CONFIRMED AND LEAKING LIQUID WAS IN FACT GASOLINE. CREW MEMBER BEGAN UNLOADING THE VAN TRAILER TO GAIN ACCESS TO THE LEAKING DRUM. THE CREW REMOVED THE LEAKING DRUM FROM THE PALLET AND PLACED IT INTO A SALVAGE DRUM FOR CONTAINMENT. THE LEAKING DRUM HAD BEEN PLACED INTO THE SALVAGE DRUM UPSIDE DOWN EXPOSING THE HOLE FOR VISUAL CONFIRMATION. THE CREW REPORTED THE LEAKING DRUM DID HAVE A HOLE IN THE BOTTOM OF THE RECONDITIONED CLOSED TOP DRUM. THE HOLE IN THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM APPEARED TO RESEMBLE A NAIL PUNCTURE. A CLOSER INSPECTION OF THE PALLET REVEALED NO NAILS PROTRUDING UP AND OUT OF THE PALLET. THE CREW STATED WOODEN PALLET WAS IN GREAT SHAPE AND ALL OF THE NAILS WERE SUNK, INTO THE WOOD, NOT PROTRUDING UP. THE PUNCTURE TO THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM CAUSED BY A NAIL ASSOCIATED WITH THE PALLET WAS RESTING ON. WITH THE LEAKING DRUM SECURED THE CREW PROCEEDED TO CLEANUP THE EXCESS FROM THE TRAILER FLOOR AND THE EXCESS LIQUID THAT HAD LEAKED OUT OF THE TRAILER ONTO THE PARKING LOT. THE GRANULAR ABSORBENT MATERIAL USED DRY UP THE 1/2 GALLON RELEASE HAD BEEN PLACED INTO THE SALVAGE DRUM WHICH CONTAINED THE LEAKING DRUM. ALL CARGO ITEMS WERE RELOADED BACK ONTO THE TRAILER.
column169: Recommendations, in the future new drums not re-conditioned drums and inspect all wooden pallets prior to use to ensure there are no protruding nails or sharp object that would lead to or cause a liquid release.

column168: A roll-off container operated by Clean Harbors Environmental arrived at the Clean Harbors facility in Seymour Ct for the purpose of staging for delivery the next day  to the intended waste management facility. Upon a routine inspection of the container the driver discovered material coming from the rear door of the roll-off container. The driver immediately applied speedy dry and contained the material. A  response crew opened the roll off door, added sorbent and resealed the rear  door identified as the cause of the release. The container was secured for continued transportation.
column169: At the time the driver accepted the container for transportation, no evidence of leaking was observed. The container was used for and emergency response to clean leaking material form a vehicle accident. Due to wet and snowy weather conditions the waste must have contained water which thawed and leaked thru the seams of the roll off. Response crews were advised to inspect gaskets and closures to assure the container is sealed tightly.

A BNSF mechanical carman performing a terminal inspection of railcars in a receiving track in the railyard, reported tank car UTLX 200316 on an adjacent track emanating a commodity odor with a liquid stain on its side shell. UTLX 200316 was cordoned-off in the railyard. BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders immediately inspected UTLX 200316.  The responders reported finding the leak source at the liquid valve's threaded connection. The liquid valve was not tool tight (hand tight only) on its threaded connection which allowed commodity to escape at this threaded area. The liquid valve was properly tool tightened which ended any further commodity release. Non-evaporated spillage was wiped.   The BNSF employee that reported UTLX 200316 emanating commodity odors complained of inhalation exposure from the commodity vapors from UTLX 200316. The employee was taken to a local hospital and after an examination was released to return to work.

Norfolk Southern personnel reported a strong odor from the area around tank car ETCX222707.  The car was found to be leaking product from the bottom outlet.  Norfolk Southern dispatched HEPACO to investigate the release.  Upon inspection the leak was found to be coming from between the tank and the bottom outlet valve flange. column168: Univar driver was making a IBC transfer delivery at Slippery Rock Municipal Water Plant.  Univar has a special permit for this operation.  (DOT SP-12412)  Driver was unloading Caustic Soda 30% solution into customer’s storage tank using two transfer hoses and a diaphragm pump.  The driver went inside the customer's building to use the restroom.  Upon return to the transfer, the hose connected to the pump outlet was disconnected and product was spilling onto the concrete.  The hose cam-lock connection became loose and disconnected from the pump.  The transfer was stopped and approximately 150 gallons of product was released onto the concrete and some made its way into a storm drain.  The customer washed down the remaining spilled product into the storm drain.  The storm drain leads to an engineered catch basin.  The product was treated on-site.
column169: The Driver failed to follow standards and procedures by not properly securing all connections and leaving a product transfer while in process.  All connects should be secured by the use of Velcro strap or wire ties.  Reviewed incident with all drivers.  Document on training sheet.  Re-train all drivers on DOT special permit SP-12412 &   Document on training sheet.  Purchase Velcro straps and ensure all drivers have in tool box.  Discipline for the driver involved with this incident.

column168: Norfolk Southern personnel reported a noise and fire from the top of tank car SHPX206604, possibly near the relief valve.  Norfolk Southern dispatched HEPACO, an emergency response contractor, to investigate the problem. HEPACO found no fire when they arrived.  The response time for HEPACO was about 2 hours.  The car was tested with an infra red thermometer gun.  No highly elevated temperatures were noted.  HEPACO personnel applied a 0-200psi pressure gauge to the car.  The pressure in the car was not high enough to move the gauge.  HEPACO utilized a four gas meter to test LEL levels around the man-way and valves for any leak source.  No readings were noted.  Norfolk Southern requested HEPACO inspect the relief valve and open the man-way to check for damage to the gasket.  When HEPACO began venting the pressure from the car through the vapor line the four gas meter indicated carbon monoxide at levels up to 650ppm indicating a fire may have occurred inside the car.  Once depressurized, the man-way was opened.  The gasket was found to have wear but intact.  HEPACO personnel found no fire but reported what appeared to be soot on the interior of the man-way lid and nozzle.      Norfolk Southern placed a Hazmat Hold on the tank car and ordered laboratory sampling by a third party be conducted on the tank interior and its contents to test for signs of combustion.  The forensic analysis of those samples indicated a fire did occur inside of tank car SHPX206604.  A copy of that report is attached to this 5800.    The car was also inspected by representatives of Union Tank Car, the car owner American Railcar Leasing.
column169: The information obtained from this incident has been forwarded to the car owner, the AAR Tank Car Committee and the Renewable Fuels Association for further study.

column168: Driver of vehicle ran over curb and large rock with left axles of trailer which caused center of gravity for product in tank to shift causing a rollover. The shell of one compartment developed a crack and was leaking onto the asphalt driveway at a slow rate.  Driver placed a bucket under release but not before approx. 60 to 120 gallons was spilled. (There was a small amount of gas left on the trailer that could not be pumped over.) Absorbent pads and pigs were also used until a cleanup contractor arrived on site. There was no contact/drainage of the product into any drains, sewers, or waterways.  Each compartment was drilled to allow the pump-out to another trailer for delivery elsewhere. The trailer was then righted using several tow rigs.  Tractor & trailer where held for inspection by PA State Police but release several days later with no issues found. Video was available and viewed by management. A check of the on board recording device revealed the tractor was moving at 5 mph. On rollover the shear forces involved pulled the fifth wheel plate and mounts free of the tractor frame leaving the tractor upright. The inspection by the State Police & company revealed no defects of the fifth wheel plate or pin. Any remedial actions needed are to be handled by the spill contractor performing tests to determine ground and asphalt contamination. Samples are to be taken at site so there will likely be additional costs for spill remediation not shown on this report.  Additionally we are anticipating charges for loss of sales for the McDonalds & Exxon as they were unable to service customers during this period.

column168: A vehicle operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc was en route from the shipper’s location to the intended waste management facility.  During the course of the trip, the driver made a routine stop at a 10 day transfer facility for the purpose of consolidating less than truck load quantities on a single transport vehicle for continued transportation. Upon inspection of the trailer, employee noticed one of the totes leaking from dump valve at bottom of IBC.  The material was transferred to a new IBC.  While inspecting the valve on the IBC that leaked, it was noted that the gasket on the valve cap was damaged and misaligned.  It was also noted that debris inside the vall valve had prevented the valve from fully closing. Facility personnel assembled a response team who proceeded to place the contents into a suitable IBC container. In addition, all clean-up debris and materials used to decontaminate the floor of the trailer were collected and placed into the salvage drum. Once complete, the container was secured and was placed onto the trailer for continued transportation
column169: Drivers will continue to inspect each container during staging period as well as  before it is loaded and will take all appropriate actions should a container show evidence of reduced structural integrity. column14: Riverview Road 0.3mi W of Q St
column168: rior to the tractor trailer tipping Jacob was traveling west on Riverview road 0.3 miles west of Q St near Ponca City, OK at 28mph. The road crosses over the Chikaskia river with a bridge known as Gun Barrel bridge. As you pass over the bridge the road slopes down into a valley. The road in this valley was extremely muddy. According to the tire tracks, the driver was directing the vehicle at a slight angle compared to the road. That angle would cause him to run off the road around 150yards post bridge unless he corrected. It shows that the driver did not correct his trajectory until his steer tires were around 2 feet from the right edge of the road. As he turned his steer tires the momentum of the vehicle on the muddy road caused him to continue straight. This resulted in the tractor departing the roadway on the right and tipping onto the passenger side. As the vehicle came to rest on the its passenger side, a small amount of clear diesel (2gal) leaked from the saddle tank of the tractor. No product was released from the trailer.

column168: The container was found to have white paint releasing out of the rear doors. Inspection of the container determined eight one-gallon paint cans released their contents. The cause of the release was inadequate blocking and bracing. The load was secured with load locks and dunnage bags and had no load separation between the stacked shipment. The dunnage bags ruptured allowing the lading to shift. The paint cans were smashed against the load locks and four of the cans fell to the floor releasing their entire contents. The spill was remediated and the leaking cans were placed in an overpack drum. The container was released for transportation and was delivered without further incident.

column168: The driver of a tractor and Portable tank  lost control due the passenger side steering wheel went off the roadway to the soft shoulder causing the unit to roll to its right side. Hazmat was released from the pressure relief valve due to over-pressurization to the tank body and a 1'x 1' area of the soil shoulder. There was no reported damage to the relief valve. A cleanup contractor was dispatched to remediate the release. The incident was reported to the NRC because local police and fire advised that the roadway was a main road and that a nearby elementary school issued a shelter in place. Our Reference 45196.

column168: Linde tractor trailer (cargo tank) was traveling east along Hwy 90. Driver stopped at a rail road crossing approximately one mile South East of the intersection of Hwy 90 and Route 85 by Jeanerette, LA. A third party vehicle traveling at significant speed (65mph)struck the trailer in the rear. This resulted in a cracked vent pipe and broken discharge line. Local Fire/EMS responded to the accident scene. Louisiana State Police HAZMAT Team and Louisiana Department of Environmental Quality also responded.      Approximately 50 gallons of liquid oxygen was released through venting and leakage during a period of 6 hours. Attempts to control product loss included isolating/diverting Liquid Oxygen away from damaged lines. All liquid oxygen was either transfered to another vessel or vented to atmosphere.
column169: Linde vehicle was lawfully fully stopped at a railroad crossing as requried of all vehicles transporting hazardous materials.  The other driver failed to identify that the vehicle was stopped and struck the Linde unit from behind.  There is not much tha the Linde driver could have done.  Regulations for stopping at crossings of high speed roadways could be ammended that all such crossing have physical barriers when a train is approaching rather than requiremeing stopping all times by HM carriers.

A LOCAL SUBCONTRACTOR WAS CONTACTED WHO IMMEDIATELY RESPONDED TO THE SITE, WIPING DOWN THE TANKER AND PLACING THE USED RAGS, PPE,AND ABSORBENTS FROM THE ASPHALT INTO A DOT-APPROVED 55 GALLON DRUM TO BE TAKEN FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.

column168: UNIT WAS EASTBOUND ON WEST ASH CREEK ROAD, AT APPROXIMATELY 15MPH DUE TO SNOW/SNOW PACK CONDITIONS. TRAILER IN TOW STARTED SLIDING DOWN THE SOUTH ROAD EMBANKMENT.  WHILE TRYING TO KEEP THE TRAILER UP ON THE ROAD, THE TRAILER PULLED THE TRACTOR AND SLID INTO THE ROAD DITCH. AT THE POINT BOTH UNITS TIPPED ONTO IT'S RIGHT SIDE.  THE AIR INLET TUBING WAS DAMAGED/BROKEN ON IMPACT. PRODUCT BEGAN TO SPEW OUT BROKEN TUBING.  SNOW WAS AT OR ABOUT 4' DEEP ON ROAD WITH A NORTH WIND CAUSING DRIFTING ON THE SOUTH SIDE OF THE ROAD.  UPON INVESTIGATION BY DAWES COUNTY SHERIFF, (SCOTT SWITCHARD) OF THE TIRE MARKS, WEATHER CONDITIONS AND PICTURES OF THE ACCIDENT SCENE, AND DRIVER STATEMENTS CORELATE WITH THE FINDINGS.

column168: On February 16, 2015, a load of UN3105 Organic Peroxide Type D Liquid being shipped by R&L Carriers was found to be damaged. The release was discovered during unloading, but damage occurred during loading. Approximately 4 gallons of material released from (4) separate 1-gallon containers within 1 box. The material released onto the trailer floor. No soils, drains or waterways were impacted. The skid of boxes was improperly loaded as it was slid against the trailer wall crushing the box. Terra contracting responded to decontaminate the trailer floor and containerize all waste and damaged containers. No injuries or exposures resulted. The site was restored to its previous condition.

In the process of making a delivery of Sodium Hypochlorite to customer aboveground storage tank, the CMV operator made a 2" diameter hose connection to the hard pipe, but failed to make a required second connection leading to the aboveground storage tank. Customer failed to have its employee in attendance during offloading to ensure a proper offloading, contrary to this customer's established procedure.  After the connection to the hard pipe only, the CMV operator returned to the rear of the cargo tanker and opened the valve to offload product through the line.  However, one end of the transfer system (flex hose combined with hard pipe) remained unattached.  This caused product to flow out of the pipe to the ground. Less than thirty (30) seconds after offloading began, the CMV operator visually observed spill occurring and immediately shut off the flow of product from the cargo tanker.  The CMV operator failed to notify anyone of the event.  The customer became aware of the spill after CMV operator left customer premises; customer reported that some of the product discharged to the customer's property causing damage to the property.
column169: A) CMV operator suspended, and upon return to work from suspension, was demoted as well as placed on probation for six (6) months.    B) Work with customer to resolve multiple connection, improve their equipment and operations so that only one connection for offloading product to the customer aboveground storage tank is required.    C) Ensure customer employee is present during the offloading of sodium hypochlorite at this location.

A.On 02/16/2015, at 1315, personnel on the CSXT train K08014 reported the train was involved in a derailment. K08014 is a loaded unit train of petroleum crude oil. The derailment involved multiple rail cars including GATX 286241. The bottom outlet valve was sheared off of GATX 286241 causing a release of 7590 gallons that was involved in fire.  The shipper Plains Marketing, local EMS agencies, West VA DEP and federal agencies (FRA, EPA, NRC) were notified.  (CHEMTREC Report #2015-02-16-00126). Multiple CSXT emergency response contractors and CSXT personnel were dispatched to the scene to contain and clean up spilled material.     Cause Code: T221 Broken Rail  Vertical split head  NARRI: (2+5+5) x (5+5) = 200    B.On 02/16/2015, at 1315, personnel on the CSXT train K08014 reported the train was involved in a derailment. column168: A BNSF mechanical carman inspecting an inbound BNSF train in the railyard reported entrained tank car OXAX 3306 leaking commodity from the bottom of the tank near the B-end body bolster pad weld. A catch receptacle was placed under OXAX 3306. Contract responders reported observing a crack approximately 7 inches in length extending from the edge of the B-end welded body bolster pad. The responders applied sealant (plug and dike) on and around the crack, then positioned and secured a 'compression diaper' (rubber padding secured by 2 inch wide ratchet straps) over this area. Afterwards the commodity release stopped.  OXAX 3306 was carefully moved and isolated over a containment receptacle in the railyard while awaiting lading transfer into another suitable tank car. OXAX 3306 continued to be monitored.  On 2/24/2015, the commodity within OXAX 3306 was transferred into UTLX 200025 without further incident. On 3/02/2015, OXAX 3306 was cleaned and purged of all hazardous material. Captured commodity from the catch receptacle was placed into a 55 gallon disposal drum. Impacted ballast and soils were excavated and placed into another 55 gallon disposal drums. All disposal drums including those that captured rinsate liquids from the OXAX 3306 cleaning process were earmarked for appropriate disposal.
column169: No additional comments.

column58: Bottom Outlet Valve; Piping or Fittings
column168: Carrier was tractor trailer and DOT 407 200-bbl tanker loaded with 175 barrels of crude oil. Carrier was traveling north on US 271 going approximately 45 mph. As the carrier approached the intersection of N. Point Pleasant Rd, a vehicle driven by Lane Buchanan was being chased by East Mountain police north on N. Point Pleasant Rd at a high rate of speed. Mr. Buchanan's vehicle struck the Carrier's trailer at the intersection of US 271 and N. Point Pleasant Rd. It is estimated Mr. Buchanan's vehicle was traveling in excess of 90 mph at time of accident. Mr. Buchanan's vehicle slid under the trailer, destroying all of the pipes, fittings, valves and pump on the trailer. Mr. Buchanan's vehicle continued out the other side of the trailer and struck another vehicle that was traveling south on US 271. Mr. Buchanan died shortly after the incident from injuries suffered in the crash. Police and emergency personnel were on scene in seconds due to the active police chase.  KHP Global immediately dispatched our local operations manager and called a local remediation company (OMI) - both arrived on scene within 45-60 minutes. OMI immediately stopped the leakage from the trailer due to the damaged valves, and commenced a remediation of the site. It is estimated that no more than 20 barrels of crude oil were spilled on the roadway and side of road - all of which was cleaned up within 24-48 hrs after incident. The insurance company's remediation specialist (Cura Emergency Services), continues to work with TxDOT and TX Commission on Environmental Quality to ensure full clean up of site.
column169: There was nothing that could have been done to avoid this incident, or improve or prepare for response. The company responded as fast as possible considering the remote location of the crash, and what could easily have been a complete loss of 175 barrels was mitigated to less than 20 barrels by the fast actions of the mitigation team on site.
column198: KHP Global Inc dba Veteran Energy Transport

A CEVA Logistics Tanker was involved in a single vehicle collision with a CSX train resulting in the release of approximately 1467 gallons of diesel fuel to a section of asphalt roadway, a section of dirt roadway and an on site creek adjacent to the rail road tracks. CSX personnel coordinated all response, remediation and disposal activities. CSX personnel trans-loaded the remaining diesel fuel from the over turned tanker into a replacement tanker on site (approximately 5933 gallons )
Driver began to unload and consignee piping between shut off valve and storage tank burst. Driver shut down process and the consignee cleaned the product that was not caught in a bucket.
column169: We cannot predict unforeseen events such as this. All GTI can do is continue to teach our drivers how to react to emergency situations.

column168: A 330 gallon poly tote of UN3264 arrived at a shipping terminal with a small crack in a top corner of the poly tote. The cause of the damage is unknown. The released material was neutralized and collected with absorbents for pending disposal. The material in the tote was transferred into a replacement tote.

column168: PVS-NOLWOOD DELIVERY DRIVER INTENDED TO DELIVER A TOTE OF PVS-NOLWOOD SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE 12.5% SOLUTION IN A SQUARE STACKABLE TOTE NUMBER 3413 FROM A STRAIGHT BOX CARGO TRUCK. HE INTENDED TO USE A MANUAL PALLET JACK TO MOVE THE TOTE TO THE REAR OF THE BOX TRUCK CLOSE ENOUGH TO THE END SO THAT A FORK LIFT DRIVER COULD REMOVE THE TOTE FROM THE TRUCK.   AS HE PUSHED THE TOTE TO THE REAR OF THE TRUCK, THE PALLET JACK GOT HUNG UP ON THE EDGE OF DIAMOND PLATE ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRUCK. HE BACKED THE TOTE OFF, PUSHED HARDER TO GAIN MOMENTUM SO THE PALLET JACK COULD CLEAR THE EDGE OF THE PLATE. THE PALLET JACKED CLEARED THE EDGE OF THE PLATE, AND THEN STOPPED SUDDENLY AS THE WHEELS OF THE JACK WENT INTO A SLIGHT DEPRESSION IN THE DIAMOND PLATE NEAR THE LIFT GATE AT THE REAR OF THE BOX TRUCK. MOMENTUM CAUSED THE TOTE TO KEEP MOVING. THE TOTE SLID OFF THE PALLET JACK, OVER THE LIFT GATE, AND ONTO THE GROUND.  APPROXIMATELY 150 GALLONS OF MATERIAL SPILLED ONTO THE CONCRETE PAD AT THE SITE.  THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CLEANED UP BY A SPILL RESPONSE CONTRACTOR AND DISPOSED OF IN ACCORDANCE WITH FEDERAL, STATE AND LOCAL RULES AND REGULATIONS.
column169: Procedure for handling material in the storage area of box trucks and box trailers is being established and will include a requirement to install a load bar in the final e-track position. Employees shall be trained on this procedure.

column168: THE GIANT RESOURCE RECOVERY-SUMTER (GRR) RAIL HEAD FACILITY IS  A 10-DAY TRANSFER FACILITY. ON FEBRUARY 3, 2015, PRIOR TO OFF-LOADING OF CONTAINERS FROM RAILCAR GIMX516146, A CONTRACTOR DISCOVERED SMALL, INTERMITTENT DRIPS OF HAZARDOUS WASTE COMING FROM CONTAINER CHIU 250304 (CONTAINER). AT THE TIME, THE OPERATOR WAS PREPARING TO OFF-LOAD THE CONTAINERS, BY CRANE, FOR TRANS-SHIPMENT TO GIANT CEMENT COMPANY LOCATED IN HARLEYVILLE, SC. PLASTIC AND ABSORBENT MATERIAL WAS PLACED ON THE CONCRETE PAD LOCATED NEAR THE RAIL SPUR. THE CONTAINER WAS THEN OFF-LOADED AND PLACED ON THE PLASTIC AND ABSORBENT TO CAPTURE ANY ADDITIONAL LEAKS. THE CONTAINER WAS TIGHTENED AND THE LEAK STOPPED. A VERY SMALL QUANTITY OF MATERIAL (LESS THAN ONE POUND ESTIMATED) REQUIRED FROM THE LEAK. THE DROPS OF MATERIAL WERE PRIMARILY ON THE CONTAINER. NO MATERIAL WAS RELEASED OFF-SITE.

column168: Approximately 1500 lbs of AAP (a corrosive product) was spilled to secondary containment while loading a tank truck. The automatic shut off valve was not setup properly to shut off the flow upon reaching the specified value for loading. This was due to operator error. The tank truck was overfilled and material spilled into the containment area. The truck driver reported the overflow to plant personnel who shut down the loading operations. Plant personnel then proceeded to clean up the spill. The overflow lasted for approximately 3 minutes.
column169: The following actions will be taken in order to prevent recurrence.1) Update loading procedure to clarify steps for proper set up of the flow meter and shut off valve.2) Review loading/unloading procedure requirements with all operators.

column168: 1. SIMPLOT PICKUP TRUCK WAS TRAVELING SOUTH ON ROAD 36 AT 45 MPH. IT WAS PULLING A LOADED CARGO TANK TRAILER OF FUMIGANT. THERE WAS A DRIVER AND A PASSENGER ON BOARD.  2. THE FARM TRACTOR WAS TRAVELING WEST ON AVENUE 360, SPEED UNKNOWN. IT WAS PULLING A FULL WATER CARGO TANK TRAILER.   3. AT THE INTERSECTION, AVENUE 360 HAD A STOP SIGN, AND ROAD 36 DID NOT. THE FARM TRACTOR DROVE INTO THE PATH OF THE PICKUP TRUCK AND INITIATED A COLLISION. TIME OF THE COLLISION WAS APPROXIMATELY 7:30 AM.  4. THE COLLISION CAUSED THE PICKUP TRUCK AND FUMIGANT TRAILER TO SPIN COUNTER-CLOCKWISE ONTO THE DIRT SHOULDER, WHERE THE VEHICLE THE ROLLED OVER.  5. THE PICKUP TRUCK ENDED ON TOAD 36 LYING ON ITS PASSENGER SIDE. THE FUMIGANT TRAILER SHEARED OFF A WOODEN ELECTRIC POWER POLE AND WAS LODGED IN AN ALMOND TREE ON THE SIDE ON THE ROAD. SEE ATTACHED PHOTOS 1 AND 2.  6. THE FUMIGANT TRAILER WAS ROLLED OVER AT A 4 O'CLOCK POSITION. THE VENT WAS COMPROMISED BY SOFT DIRT AND GRAVEL IN THE ROLLOVER, CAUSING A SMALL LEAK OF FUMIGANT OUT OF THE VENT AND INTO THE DIRT.  7. THE LEAK AREA WAS ISOLATED, AND EMERGENCY NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE. AGENCIES INCLUDED THE CALIFORNIA HIGHWAY PATROL, THE TULARE COUNTY SHERIFF, AND THE TULARE COUNTY FIRE DEPT. WRITTEN REPORTS FROM THE HIGHWAY PATROL AND SHERIFFS DEPT. ARE ATTACHED WITH THIS REPORT.  8. THE FUMIGANT TRAILER WAS UPRIGHTED BY A TOW TRUCK, WHICH STOPPED THE LEAK AND ENDED THE EMERGENCY PORTION OF THE INCIDENT.  TIME WAS 11:20 AM. AN ESTIMATED 15 GALLONS OF TELONE II LEAKED OUT INTO THE DIRT AREA ON THE SHOULDER.  9. SIMPLOT SPILL RESPONSE PERSONNEL REMOVED APPROXIMATELY 150 GALS. OF CONTAMINATED DIRT OFF THE SITE.  10. THE SIMLOT PICKUP TRUCK AND FUMIGANT TRAILER WERE TOTALED, AND WILL BE REPLACED.
column169: 1. THE CARGO TANK AND FIXED CHASSIS TRAILER STAYED RELATIVELY INTACT DURING THE ROLLOVER AND COLLISION WITH THE POWER POLE. AS A RESULT, THE COMPANY WILL REPLACE ALL OLD TELONE TRAILERS WITH THE FIXED CHASSIS DESIGN. A TOTAL OF 5 "TURNTABLE TRAILERS" WILL BE TAKEN OUT OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SERVICE.

column168: An outbound train inspection in the railyard by a BNSF mechanical carman revealed entrained tank car UTLX 205643 with wetness on its side shell.  UTLX 205643 was carefully set-out of its scheduled outbound train and isolated in the railyard. AT 0930 hrs. PST, 2/27/2015 contract responders arrived to initiate a detailed inspection of UTLX 205643. Responders reported UTLX 205643's 165 psig set pressure relief valve (PRV) had failed. This McKenzie PRV was suspected of having a broken stem. The PRV was gagged-off and wrapped in plastic. Spillage on UTLX 205643's side shell was cleaned.  No ground impact from spillage was observed. A suitable replacement PRV was ordered. The replacement PRV was installed on 3/19/2015 without further incident.

ALL THE CONTAMINATED DIRT A TREES WERE REMOVED UNTIL THERE WAS LESS THAN THE PARTS PER MILLION PERMITTED BY THE LOCAL AND FEDERAL REGULATORY AGENCIES. FINALLY, THE RESTORATION ENVIRONMENTAL SITE WAS COMPLETELY CLEARED ON MARCH 11, 2015.

DRIVER PULLED INTO WARD TRUCKING AND PULLED UP NEXT TO THE ABOVE GROUND TANK. DRIVER HOOKED UP TO THE TANK AND PUT VELCRO STRAP ONTO THE HOSE AT BOTH THE PUMP END AND RECEIVING END. VERIFIED GAUGE AND DOUBLE CHECKED TO SEE IF ANY VISIBLE VALVE WAS PRESENT. STARTED PUMP, PUMP STARTED MAKING NOISE, HOSE STARTED JUMPING. BEFORE DRIVER COULD SHUTDOWN THE PUMP THE HOSE BLEW. DRIVER HIT THE EMERGENCY VALVE SHUTTING DOWN PRODUCT FLOW AND TRIED TO CONTAIN THE SPILL. DURATION OF THE RELEASE WAS SECONDS. ORIGINAL RELEASE REPORTED AS 100 GALLONS. AFTER CLEAN UP DRIVER WAS ABLE TO STICK TANKS TO SEE HOW MUCH PRODUCT WAS LEFT AND DETERMINE HOW MUCH PRODUCT WAS ACTUALLY SPILLED. AFTER CALCULATIONS, THE DRIVER HAD ONLY LOST 52 GALLONS OF PRODUCT ON THE GROUND. UPON RECEIVING CALL FROM DRIVER I CONTACTED THE CUSTOMER WARD TRUCKING, A&B SANITATION SERVICE FOR CLEAN-UP, OHIO EPA, NRC, GREAT WEST INSURANCE COMPANY AND ALSO KEPT IN TOUCH WITH THE DRIVER. I HAVE CONTACTED A&B SANITATION SERVICE FOR THE REPORTS AND DETAILS CONNECTED TO THE LOSS OF PRODUCT. ALSO CONTACTED INSURANCE COMPANY TO SEE IF THEY RECEIVED ANY REPORTS. THEY ARE ALSO AWAITING REPORTS. AS OF 03/18/15 NO REPORTS HAVE BEEN RECEIVED.

column168: Driver was transferring a IBC of Caustic Soda 30% at Slippery Rock Municipial water plant using two hoses and a diaphragm pump.  One of the hose connection became loose and disconnected from the pump.  Approximately 150 gallons of product was discharged onto the concrete and into a storm drain.  The storm drain leads to a engineered basin.  Customer was able to collect all spilled product and handle treatment on site.  No product was released into the environment.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: AT APPROX. 1033 HRS ON 02/13/2015 MOEDER OIL TRUCK #8 WAS WESTBOUND ON K-96 HWY. THE TRUCK WAS ENROUTE TO APPROX. 20 MILES NORTH OF SCOTT CITY, KS. IT WAS ENROUTE TO THE LANDMARK #3, FAIRLEIGH C#1 LEASE. ANOTHER VEHICLE PULLING A TRAILER WAS SLOWING TO TURN ON COUNTY ROAD "G". THE MOEDER OIL TRUCK REAR-ENDED THE TRAILER AND ROLLED IN ITS SIDE THEN CAUGHT FIRE. THE OTHER VEHICLE WAS PUSHED OFF THE ROADWAY, COMING TO REST IN THE NORTHWEST DITCH. THE MOEDER TRUCKS SADDLE TANK WAS RELEASED AS WELL AS APPROX. 20 GALLONS FROM THE CARGO TANK. THE FIRE VALVE/EXCESS FLOW VALUE BROKE OFF AND EMITTED FUEL ONTO THE ROADWAY. THE POINT OF BREAK FROM THE VALVE WAS PLUGGED BY A RAG UNTIL HAZMAT RESPONSE COULD OFF-LOAD THE FUEL. THE TOTAL CAPACITY PER THE MANUFACTURE OF THE TANK IS 3500 GALLONS HOWEVER THE METERED GALLONS OFF-LOADED WERE 3530 GALLONS. THE REASON FOR THE OVERAGE IS DUE TO THE MANUAL FILL OF THE 4 COMPARTMENT TANK. THE TANKS HAVE A "MARKER" INSIDE THAT ACTS AS A FILL GUIDELINE. IT IS ASSUMED THAT THE TOTAL PUT INTO THE TRUCK WAS NO MORE THEN 3550 GALLONS LEAVING US TO BELIEVE THAT THE POSSIBILITY OF 20 GALLONS CAME FORM THE CARGO TANK. THIS WAS NOT ANSWERED CORRECTLY ON #27 DUE TO THE PROGRAM NOT ALLOWING IT.

column168: THE PROGRESSIVE RESOURCES DRIVER WAS TRAVELING SOUTH ON US HWY 69 OUTSIDE OF THE TOWN OF LUMBERTON, TEXAS.  AS HE WAS TRAVELING, HE CROSSED OVER THE SOLID WHITE LINE OF THE ROAD STRIKING THE GUARD RAIL WITH THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE VEHICLE.  THE VEHICLE TRAVELED DOWN THE LENGHT OF THE GUARD RAIL FOR APPROXIMATELY 300 FEET.  WHEN THE TRACTOR CLEARED THE GUARD RAIL, IT CONTINUED OFF-ROAD INTO AN ADJACENT DITCH. THE VEHICLE CAME TO STOP RESTING ON THE SIDE OF THE DITCH. ONCE THE VEHICLE STOPPED, DUE TO THE ANGLE OF THE DITCH, THE VEHICLE  PROCEEDED TO ROLL ON TO ITS PASSENGER SIDE. THERE WERE NO OTHER VEHICLES INVOLVED, NO PACKAGE FAILURE AND NO RELEASE OF THE NITROGEN CONTENTS FROM THE TRAILER.
column169: REGARDING RECOMMENDATIONS OR ACTIONS TAKEN TO PREVENT RECURRENCE OF THIS EVENT, IT WAS DETERMINED AFTER AN INVESTIGATION, THAT THE EVENT MAY HAVE BEEN A RESULT OF FATIGUE BY THE DRIVER WHO HAD FAILED TO FOLLOW WORK RULES. AS PART OF  A DRIVER'S ON-BOARDING TRAINING, THEY ATTEND A DRIVER SAFETY BOOT CAMP, WHERE THE ARE INFORMED OF AIR LIQUIDE'S POLICIES PERTAINING TO DRIVER FATIGUE AND THE IMPORTANCE OF FOLLOWING THOSE POLICIES. THAT TRAINING IS ALSO EXTENDED DURING THE HANDS ON TRAINING THE NEW DRIVER'S REVEIVE WHEN THEY ARE PLACED WITH DRIVER TRAINERS. AIR LIQUIDE WILL CONTINUE ITS CURRENT PROGRAMS FOR ON-BOARDING AND MONITORING DRIVERS.

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column168: The package was unloaded with leakage noted on the box.  Examination of the inner container revealed that the container(s) had loose cap(s) and leaked.  The leakage was contained.  The cap(s) were secured.  The carton was wet but otherwise undamaged.  The undamaged portion of the package was repacked for return to shipper.

column43: CRUDE COKE OVEN TAR / CENTRIFUGE TAR
column168: ON 02/09/15 WE HAD A RELEASE OF APPROXIMATELY 100 GALLONS OF CRUDE COKE OVEN TAR AT OUR OPERATION. A DRIVER WAS LOADING THE MATERIAL FROM HIS TRAILER INTO A RAILCAR AND MISTAKENLY OVERFILLED THE CAR. THE DRIVER DID NOT FOLLOW THE CHECK IN PROCESS AND FAILED TO VERIFY THE CORRECT RAILCAR TO LOAD IN TO. OUR OPERATOR QUICKLY RESPONDED TO CONTAIN THE LEAK. THE PRODUCT, A THICK LIQUID, RAN DOWN THE SIDE OF THE RAILCAR AND LANDED ON PAVEMENT/BALLAST. WE REMOVED THE MATERIAL AND PLACED INTO 55 GAL DRUMS FOR PROPER DISPOSAL. IN ADDITION, REPRESENTATIVES FROM CLEAN HARBORS CAME ON SITE AND CLEANED THE CAR AND PERFORMED A SITE ASSESSMENT TO ENSURE ALL PRODUCT WAS PROPERLY REMOVED. CONTAINMENT AND CLEANUP ACTIVITIES (WITH DATES): SPILL BOOMS/BERMS IMMEDIATELY DEPLOYED, PRODUCT SHOVELED UP AND PLACED INTO 2 55 GALLONS DRUMS. CLEAN HARBORS NOTIFIED, ARRIVED ON SITE 2/10 APPROX 11AM WITH VAC TRUCK AND PRESSURE WASHER, WASHED RAILCAR AND VACUUMED UP WASH WATER, HAULED OFF SITE TO WASTE DISPOSAL COMPANY. SITE INSPECTION WAS PERFORMED BY CLEAN HARBORS ON 2/10 TO ENSURE NO RESIDUAL MATERIAL WAS PRESENT.
column169: A ROOT CAUSE ANALYSIS WAS PERFORMED AFTER HIS OCCURRENCE WITH THE FOLLOWING CORRECTIVE ACTIONS:  -ENSURE DRIVER DOES NOT GO INTO YARD UNTIL HE HAS THE PAPERWORK WHICH LISTS PROPER RAILCAR TO LOAD INTO  -RETRAIN OPERATORS AND OFFICE STAFF ON ENSURING WE HAVE CLEAR COMMUNICATION WITH DRIVER  -UPDATE PROCEDURE TO INCLUDE MORE DETAILS ON THE CHECK IN AND VERIFICATION PROCESS

column168: WHILE RECEIVING A DELIVERY OF DIESEL FUEL, THE CLOCK GAGE ON OUR STORAGE TANK FAILED AND GAVE THE INCORRECT READING. THE TANK OVER FILLED AND VENTED FUEL. WE CALLED FOR AN ENVIRONMENTAL COMPANY TO REPSOND AND CLEAN UP THE SPILL.
column169: THE CLOCK GAGE WAS REPLACED AND THE TERMINAL STAFF IS REQUIRED TO STICK THE TANK TO INSURE THE AMOUNT ORDERED WILL FIT IN THE TANK BEFORE DELIVERY OF THE FUEL.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: DRIVER HAD LOOSE FITTING ON HOSE AND SPILLED FIVE GALLONS ONTO GROUND.
column169: RETRAINED DRIVER ON PROPER LOADING AND UNLOADING.

column168: THE LEAK WAS DISCOVERED BY A GEORGIA DEPARTMENT OF PUBLIC SAFETY OFFICER, DURING A ROUTINE INSPECTION AT THE SCALE HOUSE. THERE WAS A SMALL LEAK FROM THE IN-TRANSIT HEAT LINE THAT EVENTUALLY FORMED A 10" PUDDLE.  DRY SWEEP WAS PLACED ON THE SPILL AND MORAN ENVIRONMENTAL RECOVERY WAS DISPATCHED TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL. A  MECHANIC CAPPED THE IN-TRANSIT HEAT LINE. WE MOVED OUR TRAILER TO THE SAVANNAH GEORGIA TERMINAL AND MORAN ENVIRONMENTAL PERFORMED A TRANS-LOAD INTO ANOTHER TRAILER AT OUT FACILITY.
column169: THE LEAKING TRAILER WAS WASHED AND TRANSFERRED TO TERMINAL SERVICE COMPANY IN TALLAHASSEE FOR INPSECTION AND REPAIRS. WE HAVE NOT REVEIVED THE ANY FURTHER INFORMATION FROM MORAN ENVIRONMENTAL OR TERMINAL SERVICE COMPANY AT THIS TIME.

column42: AMINES, LIQUID, CORROSIVE, N.O.S. OR POLYAMINES, LIQUID, CORROSIVE, N.O.S.
column168: 2 drums were wrapped on the pallet and about a cup of liquid spilled.  The terminal could not see any damage or were the leaking was coming from.  Cleaned up in house.  Both drums were put into a salavage drum.

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column168: WHILE UNLOADING DISCOVERED LEAKING PAIL. SECOND PAIL DAMAGED. PAILS PLACED INTO LINED SALVAGE DRUM PENDING DISPOSITION FROM THE SHIPPER. SPILLAGE ABSORBED AND CLEANED UP PROPERLY PENDING DISPOSAL.
column169: PRIOR LOADING TERMINAL MANAGEMENT TO DISCUSS THE IMPORTANCE OF NEVER LOADING HEAVY FREIGHT ON TOP OF LIGHTER FREIGHT WITH FREIGHT LOADERS.
column172: Metal pail, open head, capacity 10 gallons or less

column168: * NATX 302743 HAD A 5'0 HOLE AS A RESULT OF DERAILMENT.  INTERIOR CONTENTS ON FIRE.  UPON SITE COOLING, FIRE EXTINGUISHED ITSELF AND CAR WAS TRANSFERRED.    #1 - NATX 302867 INVOLVED IN DERAILMENT FOUND WITH 1X5 HOLE THAT  WAS ON FIRE FROM LEAK IN SHELL, FIRE WENT OUT WHEN LIQUID LEVERL DROPPED BELOW HOLE.    #2 - CTCX 730766 WAS INVOLVED IN DERAILMENT. IT HAD A CATASTROFIC FAILURE, (1) 5 FOOT LONG TEAR ALONG BOTTOM SUPPORT BEAM IN HEAT EFFECTED ZONE. RESPONSE TEMA UNABLE TO SEAL LEAK PRODUCT WAS LOST INTO RIVER. AROUND 50% OF LOAD WAS LOST.    #3 - DBUX 303073 WAS INVOLVED IN DERAILMENT.  BOTTOM OUTLET NOZZLE WA SHEARED OFF W/VALVE OPENED LOSING ABOUT 1/2 LOAD INTO RIVER. UPON ARRIVAL VALVE WAS CLOSED TO STOP LEAK.    #4 - NATX 302997 HAD MAJOR HEAT IMPINGMENT WITH LARGE HEAT BLISTER W/NO TEAR, BOTTOM OUTLET NOZZLE WAS SHEARD OFF WITH VALVE OPEN. UPON ARRIVAL TEAM SAW NO LIQUID COMING FROMM VALVE A LIQUID LEVEL BELOW VALVE. VALVE WAS THEN CLOSED. REMAINING PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERED AT A LATER TIME.    #5 - EAST BOUND TRAIN DERAILED @ RR MP CTCX 730782 WAS INVOLVED IN DERAILMENT ALL APLIANCES REMAINED INTACT. NO SIGNIGICANT DAMAGE TO TANK CAR.    #6 - CITX 22424 WAS INVOLVED IN DERAILMENT CAR WAS OFF RAIL AND DOWN BANK INTO RIVER BOTTOM OUTLET NOZZLE WAS SHEARD OFF W/VALVE OPEN.  RESPONDER CLOSED VALVE TO STOP LEAK SO CAR COULD BE TRANSFERED AT A LATER TIME.    #7 - CITX 224195 HAD NO SIGNIFICANT DAMAGE DUE TO DERAILMENT. ONLY MINOR DAMAGE TO VALVE HOUSING COVER.    #8 - VMSX 311153 HAD NO LEAKS OR SIGNIFICANT  DAMAGE AS A RESULT OF DERAILMENT ONLY MINOR DAMAGE FROM WRECKING ACTIVITIES    #9 - CTCX 730790 WAS INVOLVED IN DERAILMENT THERE WAS NO SIGNIFICANT DAMAGE TO TANK, NO PRODUCT WAS LOST, AND WAS TRANSFERED INTO OTHER RAILCARS AT LATER DATE.    #10 - CTCX 730034 WAS INVOLVED IN DERAILMENT ONLY WRECKING DAMAGE TO CAR, NO RELEASE OF PRODUCT    #11 - DBUX 3030187 HAD ONLY MINOR DENTS FROM DERAILMENT. DID HAVE HEAT IMPINGMENT ON UPPER END OF "B" END CAR WAS TRANSFERED AT LATER DATE

WHEN THE DRIVER BEGAN THE TRANSFER, A VENT VALVE WAS LEFT IN A PARTIALLY OPEN POSITION VENTING PROPANE VAPOR TO THE ATMOSPHERE. THE DRIVER WAS COMPLETING PAPERWORK AT THE FRONT OF THE TRUCK WHEN THE ODORANT AND VAPOR CLOUD WERE NOTICED. APPROXIMATELY 40 GALLONS OF PROPANE WERE RELEASED BEFORE EMERGENCY SHUTOFF PROCEDURES WERE ACTIVATED BY THE DRIVER EMERGENCY SERVICES WERE NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED. VAPOR CLOUD WAS ALLOWED TO DISSAPATE AFTER CLOSING OF THE LOCAL STREET FOR PRECAUTIONS. UPON INVESTIGATION, DRIVER DID NOT FULLY CLOSE VENT VALVE BEFORE UNLOADING.

column62: Misaligned Material, Component, or Device; Broken Component or Device
column168: AT ABOUT 12:50AM ON TUESDAY FEBRUARY 10TH, APP DRIVER WAS ON HIS 5TH STOP OF THE EVENING FLEET FUELING COMMERCIAL TRUCKS AT APP CUSTOMER SEATAC EXPRESS. BECAUSE HE WAS ON A LATER STOP, THE TOTAL GALLONS CARRIED IN THE TRUCK AT THAT TIME WAS ONLY ABOUT 700, AS HE HAD ALREADY DISPENSED THE REST OF IT AT OTHER STOPS. WHILE HE WAS FUELING A TANK, HE SAW WHAT LOOKED IN THE DARK LIKE SMOKE AND HEARD A NOISE COMING FROM THE OPPOSITE SIDE OF HIS TRUCK. HE QUICKLY SHUT OFF THE NOZZLE AND RAN TO THE TRUCK TO DISCOVER WAS LOOKED LIKE "SMOKE" WAS ACTUALLY A SPRAY OF FUEL COMING FROM THE PTO (POWER TAKE OFF), WHICH IS THE POWER/MOTOR FOR FUEL DISPENSING. HE TURNED OFF THE PTO AND THE TRUCK AND ACTED QUICKLY AND CREATIVELY AND RETRIEVED A LARGE PIECE OF STYROFOAM TO USE AS A CATCH BASIN COVER. HE FOLLOWED THE PATH THE FUEL WOULD TAKE AND COVERED THE CATCH BASIN AND DAMNED THE LIQUID PRODUCT WITH ABSORBENT PADS HE HAD. IT HAD BEEN RAINING SHORTLY BEFORE THE RELEASE BUT WAS NOT RAINING AT THE TIME ENOUGH TO CAUSE FLOW. BECAUSE THE STYROFOAM WASN'T LIQUID TIGHT TO THE CATCH BASIN, SOME FUEL TRICKLED IN SLOWLY, BUT HIS COVER KEPT A GOOD MAJORITY FROM ENTERING THE BASIN. ALSO, ALL FUEL THAT HAD ENTERED THE BASIN REMAINED THERE, AS THE OUTFLOW PIPE WAS ABOVE THE LIQUID LEVEL IN THE BASIN. AFTER CONTAINMENT, APP DRIVER NOTIFIED APP DISPATCH, WHO NOTIFIED APP'S HSSE MANAGER TARYN MILLER WHO RESPONDED TO SCENE. HSSE MANAGER SPOKE WITH APP DRIVER, WHO INDICATED HE ESTIMATED THE SPILL WAS LESS THAN OR EQUAL TO ABOUT 30 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL. HE HAD NO WAY TO CONFIRM THIS, HOWEVER, AS THE SPILL DID NOT OCCUR FORM THE LINE WHERE HE WAS METERING FUEL FROM. WHILE EN ROUTE TO SCENE TARYN MILLER DISPATCHED NRC ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, APP'S CLEAN-UP CONTRACTOR. ON ARRIVAL TO SCENE, IT WAS IDENTIFIED THAT THE TRUCK WAS STILL LEAKING FUEL (A BUCKET PLACED  UNDERNEATH BY DRIVER WAS CONTAINING IT), AND WE WOULD NEED APP'S ON-CALL MECHANIC TO RESPOND AS WELL. CALLS WERE THEN MADE TO NOTIFY REGULATORY AGENCIES ABOUT THE INCIDENT. TARYN MILLER FIRST CALLED THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER (REPORT# 107754), THEN THE WASHINGTON DEPARTMENT OF EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT (REPORT# 15-0490), WHO INDICATED THAT THE WASHINGTON DEPARTMENT OF ECOLOGY ON-CALL SPILL RESPONSE PARTY WOULD BE NOTIFIED AND WOULD RETURN THE CALL. THE ECOLOGY REPRESENTATIVE CALLED BACK SHORTLY AFTER AND REQUESTED INFORMATION ABOUT CLEAN-UP. WE CONFIRMED TO THEM THAT NRC ENVIRONMENTAL WAS EN ROUTE FOR CLEAN-UP AND THAT FROM WHAT WE WOULD TELL EVERYTHING WAS CONTAINED WITHING THE SINGLE CATCH BASIN.  HE SAID HE WOULD CALL BACK IF THEY NEEDED TO MAKE A SITE VISIT, BUT WE NEVER HEARD ANYTHING ELSE THAT EVENING.  APP LEAD MECHANIC GARY HARPER ARRIVED AND WORKED ON THE TRUCK TO STOP THE LEAK.  HE DRAINED THE PLUMBING LINE ATTACHED TO THE PTO AND MADE ADJUSTMENTS SO THAT IT WOULD NOT LEAK ANYMORE AND TRUCK COULD BE DRIVEN BACK TO APP'S YARD IN TACOMA, WA FOR REPAIRS.  HE INDICATED LATER THAT THE SPILL WAS CAUSED BY A WARPED FLANGE ON T
column169: WITH INCIDENT BEING CAUSED BY EQUIPMENT FAILURE, THERE ISN'T A LOT WE CAN DO. WE ALREADY HAVE A THOROUGH INSPECTION PROCESS FOR THE TRUCKS WHEN THEY ARE IN FOR SERVICE. OUR SHOP NOW KNOWS TO LOOK FOR THE TYPE OF WARPING WE SAW ON THIS TRUCK IN FUTURE INSPECTIONS. DRIVER, WHO REVEIVES HAZWOPER TRAINING ANNUALLY, ACTED QUICKLY AND RESPONSIBLY IN STOPPING PRODUCT FLOW AND CONTAINING THE SPILL, PREVENTING THIS SPILL FROM BECOMING LARGER THAN IT WAS. WE TAKE PRIDE THAT OUR DRIVER DEPLOYED HIS TRAINING SKILLS TO THINK ON HIS FEET AND USE THE LARGE PIECE OF STYROFOAM THAT ULTIMATELY PREVENTED A LOT OF THE PRODUCT FORM ENTERING THE BASIN.

column168: ON FEBRUARY 2, 2015 THE OWNER OF 547 BRITTON AVENUE STATEN ISLAND, NY 10304 HAD PLACED AN ORDER FOR A DELIVERY OF HOME HEATING OIL TO THEIR FUEL TANK LOCATED ABOVE ADDRESS. THE TRUCK WENT TO HOME AND HOOKED UP THE FUEL HOSE TO THE FILL PIPE LOCATED ON THE SIDE OF THE HOUSE. HE BEGAN TO PUMP THE OIL INTO THE TANK AND LISTENED TO THE VENT ALARM WHISTLE WHICH IS PART OF THE FUEL OIL TANK. WHEN THE WHISTLE STOPPED BLOWING HE SHUT THE PUMP OFF TO STOP PUMPING OIL. HOWEVER, ABOUT 5 GALLONS OF HOME HEATING OIL HAD SPILLED OUT OF THE VENT ALARM ONTO THE CONCRETE DEIVEWAY OF THE PREMISE. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY PLACE DOWN SPEEDY-DRY ABOSORBENT ONTO THE SPILL TO CONTAIN AND ABSORB IT. HE THEN CALLED THE OFFICE TO REPORT THE SPILL. THE OFFICE DISPATCHED A CREW TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL.  NO FUEL HAD IMPACTED ANY STREET OR WATER, IT WAS ALL CONTAINED ON THE CONCRETE DRIVEWAY DIRECTLY UNDER THE FILL PIPE.
column169: THE COMPANY DISCUSSED WITH THE DRIVER ABOUT WHAT HAD HAPPENED. WE HAD DOWN ADDITIONAL TRAINING WITH HIM AS WELL AS A REVIEW OF OPERATING PROCEDURES. WE ALSO HAD TECHNICIANS REPAIR THE VENT ALARM ON THE HOMEOWNERS TANK TO ALSO HELP AVOID ANY FUTURE PROBLEMS.

column168: ICE ON ROADWAY CAUSED A MULTIPLE VEHICLE ACCIDENT AT THIS LOCATION.  THE DIVISION SURFACE AIR (DSA) TRAILER WAS STRUCK FROM BEHIND CAUSING SEVERAL OF THE TOTES OF HAZARDOUS MATERIAL TO RELEASE THEIR CONTENTS.  DAMAGE TO THE TRAILER CAUSED THE MATERIAL TO BE RELEASED ONTO THE ROADWAY AND OTHER VEHICLES.  A CALL PLACED TO DSA AND DSA CALLED AN ENVIRONMENTAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE COMPANY.  A LOCAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM WAS DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE.  UPON ARRIVAL, THE TEAM WORKED WITH LOCAL MISSOURI DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION PERSONNEL TO PROVIDE CINDERS, A SOLID MATERIAL TO COLLECT AND REMOVE THE LIQUIDS FROM THE ROADWAY.  THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT AND HOSPITAL DECONTAIMINATED ALL AFFECTED PERSONNEL.
column169: IF DRIVING IN SNOWY OR ICY CONDITIONS WERE RESTRICTED FOR HAZMAT LOADS, THIS INCIDENT WOULD NOT HAVE HAPPENED.  ALSO, IF THERE WERE WARNING DEVICES, IE; ROAD FLARES, PATROL CAR, WITH EMERGENCY LIGHTS ACTIVATED, IN PLACE, ON A BLIND HILL AND CORNER, ADVISING OF AN ACCIDENT AHEAD, THIS CRASH WOULD NOT HAVE HAPPENED.

column168: SEE ATTACHED POLICE DIAGRAM. CARRIER'S VEHICLE WAS TRAVELING NORTH. OTHER VEHICLE WAS TRAVELING  SOUTH, RAN OFF THE ROAD, OVERCORRECTED AND CROSSED CENTER LINE CRASHING INTO CARRIER'S VEHICLE, CAUSING IT TO LEAVE THE ROADWAY AND OVERTURN.  THE HOLE TORN IN THE CARGO TANK BY THE IMPACT WAS FACING UPWARD WHEN THE VEHICLE CAME TO A REST AND THE CARGO WAS SAFELY PUMPED BY THE CARRIER WITHIN MINUTES OF THE CRASH. BETWEEN 8 AND 12 GALLONS WERE SPILLED FROM THE CARGO TANK AND CONTAINED BY EMERGENCY PERSONNEL UNTIL CARRIER ARRIVED TO RECOVER REMAINING FUEL IN CARGO TANK.  ALMOST ALL FUEL ON THE ROADWAY AND SURROUNDING CAME FROM THE VEHICLE ENGINE TANKS FROM BOTH VEHICLES AS THEY BOTH RUPTURED DURING THE COLLISION.
column169: CONSIDERING AN EFFECTIVE 90 MPH IMPACT (45MPH + 45MPH) THE TANK SUFFERED MINIMAL DAMAGE AND ALMOST NO PRODUCT WAS SPILLED. THE ACCIDENT COULDN'T HAVE BEEN AVOIDED BY THE CARRIER. THE OTHER DRIVER WAS A TRAINEE (IN TRAINING AT THE TIME OF THE CRASH). THE REHEARSED RESPONSE OF THE CARRIER (FUEL RECOVERY), AND EMERGENCY PERSONEL DEMONSTRATE HOW A DANGEROUS SITUATION WAS CONTROLLED AND AVOIDED.

column42: FORMALIN, SOLUTIONS, WITH NOT LESS THAN 25 PERCENT FORMALDEHYDE
column168: A THIRD PARTY COMPANY WAS DELIVERING A TANK TRUCK LOAD (APPROXIMATELY 49,000 LBS) OF 37% FORMALDEHYDE WATER SOLUTION TO BAKER HUGHES TO BE OFF LOADED INTO THE FACILITY'S STORAGE TANK. THE DRIVER THOUGHT THAT THE TRANSFER WAS COMPLETE AND DROVE AWAY FROM THE UNLOADING BROKE AWAY FROM THE TANK TRUCK AND THE REMAINING FORMALDEHYDE IN THE TRAILER STARTED TO SPILL ONTO THE IN-PAINT ROAD. AN OPERATOR IN THE AREA SAW THE INCIDENT AND DONNED HIS RESPIRATOR AND STOPPED THE TRUCK DRIVER. THIS EMPLOYEE THEN HIT THE EMERGENCY SWITCH ON THE TRAILER WHICH CLOSED THE TRAILER VALVE AND DONNED SCBA'S AND BEGAN TO WASH THE SPILLED FORMALDEHYDE WITH THE FIRE WATER BACK TO THE SUMP SYSTEM LOCATED AT THE TRUCK UNLOADING SPOT.    THE FORMALDEHYDE SPILL WAS WASHED DOWN WITH WATER FOR THE FOLLOWING REASONS: THE GROUND WAS ALREADY WET FORM A RAIN EVENT THAT OCCURRED EARLIER IN THE MORNING, THE IN-PLANT ROAD SLOPES BACK TO THE SUMP SYSTEM, THE SUMP SYSTEM WAS ISOLATED AND WATER IS AN EXCELLENT CONTROL MATERIAL FOR CONTROLLING VAPORS.    DURING THE INCIDENT, ALL PLANT PERSONNEL WERE SHELTERED INSIDE THEIR DESIGNATED SHELTER BUILDINGS AND AIR MONITORING WAS CONDUCTED DOWNWIND OF THE RELEASE WITH A DRAGER TUBE TO ENSURE NO VAPORS WERE LEAVING THE FACILITY. A NOTIFICATION VIA THE EMERGE SYSTEM, A COMMUNITY NOTIFICATION SYSTEM, WAS ISSUED TO NOTIFY THE COMMUNITY AND SURROUNDING NEIGHBORS OF THE RELEASE.
column169: THE FACILITY HAS UPDATED THEIR STAND OPERATING PROCEDURES (SOPS) WITH ADDITION MEASURES TO TAKE TO PREVENT A TRUCK FROM LEAVING THE TRANSFER LOCATION BEFORE THE TRANSFER IS COMPLETE.  THESE MEASURES INCLUDE:    1. DRIVER REMOVES THE TRAILER AIR HOSE AND THE OPERATOR INSTALLS A LOCK ON THE AIR LINE HOSE THAT REMAINS IN PLACE UNTIL THE LOADING OR UNLOADING IS COMPLETE AND THE LOCK IS REMOVED BY THE OPERATOR.  2. THE OPERATOR PLACES A WHEEL CHOCK IN FRONT OF THE FRONT DRIVER'S SIDE CAB TIRE IN ADDITION TO A TRAILER TIRE CHOCK.  3. THE OPERATOR PLACES A YELLOW BARRICADE IN FRONT OF ALL TRUCKS WHILE BEING LOADING OR UNLOADED AS A REMINDER THAT THE TRANSFER IS STILL TAKING PLACE.

column168: ON 2/25/15 AT AROUND 13:45 OUR DRIVER UNHOOKED THE TRANSPORT TRUCK FROM OUR TANKER. THEN AROUND 15:35 SOME OF OUR WAREHOUSE WORKERS AND CUSTOMERS WATCHED AND HEARD THE TANKER FALL FORWARD AND HIT THE GROUND. THE LANDING GEAR HAD WEAKENED AND BENT WHICH RIPPED A 3 INCH TEAR INTO THE TANKER IN THE BOTTOM FRONT CONTAINER. WE THEN CALLED 911 AND LET THEN KNOW WHAT HAD HAPPENED AND HAZMAT. WE THEN PROCEED TO OPEN THE PIGS TO STOP/SLOW DOWN THE SPILL, PLACED BOOMS AND PADS AROUND THE CONTAINER TO ABSORB THE FUEL THAT HAD SPILLED, PLACED PUTTY INTO THE RIPPED AREA WHICH HAD STOPPED THE LEAK, WHICH WAS AROUND 200 GALLONS. DUE TO A CREEK BEING NEARBY ABOUT 100FT WE ALSO PLACED BOOMS FOR PRECAUTIONS. WE THEN PUMPED THE REMAINING FUEL INTO OUR STATIONERY TANK.    CLEAN UP WAS DONE IN HOUSE, BASED ON THE RESULTS OF THE SOIL TEST, DEQ IS CLOSING THE INCIDENT FILE, NO FURTHER ACTION REQUIRED BY DEQ.
