column168: DRIVER HAULING LOAD OF CRUDE OIL OVERTURNED TRUCK AND TRAILER.  REAR TRAILER WHEELS LEFT ROADWAY SURFACE AND WERE CAUGHT IN SOFT SHOULDER CAUSING THE TRAILER TO OVER-TURN, WHICH THEN CAUSED THE TRACTOR TO ROLL-OVER.    APPROXIMATELY 5 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL LEAKED FROM THE CAP ON THE TRUCK FUEL TANK ONTO THE ROADWAY.  APPROXIMATELY 8 GALLONS OF CRUDE OIL LEAKED FROM THE TOP HATCH OF THE TRAILER INTO THE DITCH.  THE DRIVER TIGHTENED/SECURED BOTH THE FUEL CAP AND TOP HATCH UPON EXITING THE TRUCK TO PREVENT ANY ADDITIONAL FUEL OR CRUDE OIL FROM SPILLING.  FUEL AND OIL WERE CLEANED UP WITHIN 12 HOURS OF SPILL BY CLEAN UP CONTRACTOR.    TRUCK AND TRAILER WERE A TOTAL LOSS DUE TO THE DAMAGE THAT WAS ENCURRED.
column169: ROLL-OVER PREVENTION TRAINING IS CONDUCTED WITH ALL NEW EMPLOYEES AND IT HAS BEEN ADDED TO THE 2ND QUARTER COMPANY REGIONAL SAFETY MEETING AGENDAS.    DRIVER RESPONSIBLE FOR THIS ACCIDENT AND SPILL WAS TERMINATED.

column168: DRIVER WAS JUST STARTING TO CLIMB A WILL, HE WAS UNDER FULL POWER, HAD MADE A 10TH GEAR SHIFT TO 9TH GEAR. AS HE PREPARED TO MAKE HIS 9TH GEAR TO 8TH GEAR SHIFT, HE SAID HE FELT THE TRUCK SHAKE VIOLANTLY. HE LOOKED IN HIS REAR VIEW MIRROR AND SAW THE TRAILER ON ITS WAY TO ROLLING OVER. HE BROUGHT THE TRUCK/TRAILER TO A STOP AND DISCOVERED THAT THE TRAILER PACKAGE HAD BEEN COMPROMISED RESULTING IN A FUEL SPILL.
column169: DRIVER WAS SEND FOR A DRUG/ALCOHOL POST ACCIDENT SCREENING. (NEGATIVE). DRIVER WAS INTERVIEWED ON THE EVENTS THAT RESULTED INTHE SPILL. HE WAS SENT FOR A POST ACCIDENT HEALTH EVALUATION AND WAS RELEASED BACK TO DUTY. A COMPANY SAFETY MEETING  WAS HELD, TO DISCUSS THE EVENT. BECAUSE WE COULD NOT DETERMINE THE CAUSE OF THE SPILL WAS, THERE HAVE BEEN NO PREVENTATIVE ACTIONS TAKEN.

column17: SYNERGY PARTNERS, INC DBA JOHNSON OIL & LP COMPANY
column42: ETHANOL AND GASOLINE MIXTURE OR ETHANOL AND MOTOR SPIRIT MIXTURE OR ETHANOL AND PETROL MIXTURE, WITH MORE THAN 10% ETHANOL
column168: JOHNSON OIL & LP COMPANY DRIVER, KEITH MEITNER, BEGAN UNLOADING HIS TRANSPORT LOAD (APPROXIMATELY 4200 GALLONS) OF E85 AT RIVERSIDE SINCLAIR IN ESTHERVILLE, IOWA AT 10:00AM. THE CAPACITY OF THE ABOVE-GROUND TANK IS 6,000 GALLONS. BOB HOUSEMAN, EMPLOYEE OF RIVERSIDE SINCLAIR, HEARD THE ALARM AND IMMEDIATELY RAN OUT OF THE STATION. BOB HOUSEMAN IS HAZARDOUS-MATERIAL TRAINED AND SHUT THE VALVE. IT IS ESTIMATED THAT 100 GALLONS OF E85 WAS DROPPED ON THE CONCRETE AND RAN INTO A STORM SEWER. THE STORM SEWER SLOWS INTO THE LOCAL RIVER. THE RIVER WAS FROZEN OVER AND IT WAS ESTIMATED THAT 50 GALLONS OF SPILLED E85 POOLED ON TOP OF THE ICE. CLEAN-UP AND CONTAINMENT ACTION OCCURRED IMMEDIATELY WITH SAND BEING DUMPED ON THE STREET. A CONTAINMENT REA WAS MADE AND PRODUCT WAS BROOMED AWAY FROM THE SEWER SYSTEM AS WELL. A CONTAINER WAS PLACED AT THE END OF THE SEWER TO CATCH THE SEWER FLOW BEFORE ENTERING THE RIVER. THE DNR WAS CONTACTED IMMEDIATELY AND THE CITY OF ESTHERVILLE AND THE ESTHERVILLE FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED TO THE SCENE.
column169: ADDITIONAL ALARMS WERE PUT ON, 6000-GALLON TANK AT RIVERSIDE SINCLAIR, REVIEW OF THE INSTRUCTIONS ON HOW TO READ TANK GAUGE READINGS BEFORE AND AFTER DELIVERY WERE PASSED ON THE DRIVER; OWNER OF RIVERSIDE SINCLAIR MISREAD GAUGE INITIALLY AND MORE GALLONS WERE ORDERED THAN NECESSARY; REVIEW OF DRIVER PROCEDURES OCCURRED WHICH INCLUDED DRIVER TO BE NEAR TANKER TRAILER SHUT-OFF WHILE UNLOADING.
column198: SYNERGY PARTNERS, INC. DBA JOHNSON OIL INC COMPANY

column168: TRACTOR-TRAILER CRESTED A HILL GOING APPROXIMATELY 40 MPH TO DISCOVER A SEPARATE VEHICLE ACCIDENT & MULTIPLE VEHICLES PARKED ON BOTH SIDES OF THE ROADWAY.  THE DRIVER MANAGED TO SLOW A BIT BEFORE HITTING THE BLACK ICE.  HE THEN LOST CONTROL ON THE ICE, JACKKNIFED THE TRACTOR TRAILER AND WENT IN THE DITCH ON THE PASSING LANE SIDE. AS HE WENT IN THE DITCH THE 5TH WHEEL HITCH SNAPPED OFF, ALLOWING THE LOADED TRAILER TO ROLL 180 DEGREES, COMING TO REST UPSIDE-DOWN ON THE BACK OF THE TRACTOR IN JACKKNIFED POSITION. THE TRACTOR REMAINED UPRIGHT. LOCAL EARTH-MOVING CONTRACTOR BROUGHT CLAY AND EQUIPMENT TO BUILD A DIKE TO PROTECT NEARBY WATERWAYS IN THE EVENT THE TANKER WOULD RUPTURE DURING OFFLOADING AND RIGHTING THE TRAILER. THE TRAILER REMAINED UPSIDE-DOWN FOR 2 HOURS BEFORE ANOTHER TANKER ARRIVED TO OFFLOAD. DURING THIS TIME, THE DRIVER SAYS IT WAS LEAKING VERY SLOWLY. THE TANKER WAS TURNED RIGHT SIDE UP ABOUT 4 HOURS AFTER THE INCIDENT AND DURING THAT PROCESS, THE FRAME RAIL OR SOME OTHER PIECE ON THE TRACTOR PIERCED A 2.5" HOLE IN THE TOP OF THE TANKER. THERE WAS ALSO A 1/2 BY 1/4 INCH TEAR IN THE TOP OF THE TOP OF THE TANKER. A PROTECTIVE SECTION OF FLAT ALUMINUM  ON THE TRAILER TOP WAS ALSO TORN AS SHOWN IN THE ATTACHED PHOTO. THE OFFLOAD FUEL WAS DELIVERED AND THERE WAS MORE FUEL RECOVERED FROM THE TANKER AFTER IT WAS UPRIGHT, GIVING US THE GALLONS RELEASED.
column169: - DRIVER EDUCATION - WHEN TO CALL SUPERVISOR ABOUT WORSENING ROAD CONDITIONS.  - SUPERVISOR EDUCATION ABOUT WHEN TO PULL VEHICLES OFF ROAD  - TANKER PERFORMED WELL UNDER CIRCUMSTANCES

column168: THE DANCO DRIVER (RICK BORG) ENTERED THE ROLFSON OIL FACILITY AS ALL DANCO DRIVERS HAVE NUMEROUS TIMES PER OUR STANDARD OPERATING PROCEDURES.  HE HOOKED UP THE HOSE ON THE DRIVER'S SIDE AND EVERYTHING ON THE PASSENGER SIDE AND STAYED THERE AS REQUIRED.  AFTER A FEW MINUTES HE NOTICED FUEL COMING FROM UNDER THE TRAILER.  HE IMMEDIATELY HIT THE EMERGENCY SHUT-OFF BUT THE FUEL THAT WAS IN-TRANSIT (HOSES, ETC.) KEEPS GOING.  HE WENT AROUND THE BACK OF THE TRAILER AND SAW FUEL SPRAYING OUT OF THE LOADING TUBE ON THE RISER AND SAW FUEL WAS GOING BEHIND THE TANKS AS WELL. TO BETTER EXPLAIN, IMAGINE THE HOSE FROM THE DANCO TANKER GOING INTO THE ROLFSON API HOOK-UP.  FROM THERE, THE FUEL GOES UP AND AROUND TO FLOW INSIDE OF THE ROLFSON TANK AND INTO THEIR LOADING TUBE, WHICH IS UP IN THE AIR HIGH ENOUGH TO GO OVER TRUCKS AND USED TO FILL SMALLER TANKS FORM THE LARGE TANK DANCO WAS FILLIN UP.  THE PROBLEM WAS THE SHUT-OFF ON THE END OF THE LOADING TUBE WAS LEFT OPEN (LIKE THE END OF A GARDEN HOSE WITH THE SPRAYER SQUEEZED OPEN WHEN YOU TURN ON THE SPIGOT AND WATER SPRAYS EVERYWHERE!).  WHEN ANYONE OPENS A VALVE OR SHUT-OFF OF ANY TYPE, ANYWHERE, THEY SHOULD BE RESPONSIBLE FOR CLOSING IT. ALSO, THAT LOAD TUBE IS HIGH UP A SET OF PORTABLE, METAL STAIRS THAT DANCO DRIVERS DO NOT USE OR TOUCH.  THE DANCO DRIVER THEN CALLED DISPATCH AND SPOKE TO SHAWN DUNCAN (A DISPATCHER WHO IS NO LONGER AN EMPLOYEE WITH DANCO) TO REPORT THE SPILL AND THEN CALLED ROLFSON TO TELL THEM WHAT HAPPENED.  AT THE TIME, ROLFSON SAID THE SPILL WAS NOT A BIG DEAL. SHAWN DUNCAN WAS TASKED TO COMPLETE THIS INCIDENT REPORT BUT DID NOT DO SO BEFORE LEAVING DANCO.  THE DANCO OWNERS BELIEVED THE INCIDENT REPORT WAS COMPLETED AND TURNED IN UNTIL GAIL TWITTY (DOT) CONTACTED JODI GERADS (OWNER) TO SAY THE INCIDENT REPORT WAS NEVER RECEIVED. I WAS BROUGHT ON BOARD 2 WEEKS AGO TO ADDRESS THIS (AND ANY OTHER DOT NEEDS IN THE FUTURE), CREATE DRIVER TRAINING MANUALS INCLUDING PROACTIVE SAFETY MEASURES, ALONG WITH GENERAL OPERATIONS AND FUNCTIONS.  I APOLOGIZE FOR THIS NOT GETTING TO YOU SOONER AND HOPE YOU CAN GIVE US A CHANCE TO GET THIS RIGHT. THIS LACK OF REPORTING IN A TIMELY MANNER WILL NOT HAPPEN AGAIN.
column169: UNFORTUNATELY, DANCO DRIVERS ARE NOT REALLY ABLE TO TAKE ANY ACTIONS TO PREVENT THIS TYPE OF RECURRENCE. THE MOST WE CAN DO IS RESPECTFULLY SUGGEST THAT ROLFSON UPDATE THEIR TRAINING PROCEDURES TO SPECIFICALLY ADDRESS THAT SHUT-OFF ON THE LOADING TUBE BE CHECKED AFTER USE TO MAKE SURE IT IS CLOSED/OFF. IF THIS IS ALREADY MENTIONED IN THEIR PROCEDURES THEN CREATING A DOUBLE-CHECK WITHIN THOSE PROCEDURES MAY BE WARRANTED. IT IS ILLOGICAL TO ASK A DANCO DRIVER TO CLIMB THOSE RISERS TO CHECK THAT SHUT-OFF ON THE LOADING TUBE.  IT IS A ROLFSON FACILITY AND A ROLFSON RESPONSIBILITY.    WITH REGARDS TO THIS INCIDENT REPORT, QUESTION 25, IN PART III WAS DIFFICULT TO COMPLETE BASED ON THIS SITUATION.  THE ONLY FAILURE WAS HUMAN-RELATED ALL THE WAY THROUGH.  NOTHING MECHANICAL FAILED SO ADDING "HUMAN FAILURE" MAY NEED TO BE ADDED TO THE "WHAT FAILED:".

column168: RICHARD FLYNN (TOPEKA TRANSPORT DRIVER) WAS NB ON HWY 45 IN WESTON MO AT APPX 10 PM ON 2 -4-15 WHEN A PICKUP TRUCK BEING PURSUED BY THE WESTON MO PD RAN A STOP SIGN AND STRUCK TRAILER 9258 ON THE PASSENGER SIDE DAMAGING THE LOADING HEADS AND REAR AXLE. RICHARD WAS LOADED WITH 6300 G OF NL AND 1000G OF DF IN THE ROADWAY. RICHARD STATED THE OFFICER CHASING THE PICK UP ARRESTED THE DRIVER AND TRANSPORTED HIM FROM THE SCENE IN HIS POLICE CRUISER. RICHARD SUPPLIED THE WESTON PD WITH HIS LICENSE MED CARD AND VEHICLE INFO BUT WAS NOT GIVEN ANY INFO REGARDING THE OTHER DRIVER. THE OFFICER DIRECTED RICHARD TO A TREX CONVENIENCE STORE APPX 2 BLOCKS NORTH TO GET OFF THE ROADWAY. THE WESTON FD ARRIVED SHORTLY AFTER THE ACCIDENT AND APPLIED ABSORBENT MATERIAL TO THE ROADWAY AND CLEANED UP THE SPILL IN THE ROADWAY. AN EMPTY TRANSPORT DRIVEN BY DAVID HERSH WAS DISPATCHED TO THE CONVENIENCE STORE. I ARRIVED AT APPX 1215 AM AND ASSISTED RICHARD AND DAVID IN TRANSFERRING THE FUEL BY PUMPING OUT THE COMPARTMENTS FROM THE TOP OF 9258 INTO TRANSPORT UNIT 1518/6573. DAVID THEN DELIVERED TO SUPER STORE IN ATCHISON KS.
